weather: Early AM rain w/near total cloud cover all day.

observers: Jasper Wehrmann
weather: Morning Rain made for a late start.  Open skies mixed with Cirriform; dramatic Cumulus sweeping our northern view throughout the day.  Strong cloud buildup to our east over the mountains by early afternoon.

observers: Arthur Green
weather: Quite warm for October w/cloudless skies.

observers: Jasper Wehrmann
weather: Clear skies w/encroaching Cirriform by midday.

observers: Arthur Green
weather: A pall of Cirrostratus all day w/hints of Altocumulus after midday.
remarks: Over 150 Steppe Buzzard (including one Common Buzzard B. buteo buteo) and a Long-legged Buzzard were observed heading north.  A passable beginning for spring perhaps, but rotten for autumn!

observers: Jasper Wehrmann
weather: System of Cumulonimbus early AM made way for mid AM thunderstorm; Cirriform skies by noon, holding for the remainder of the day.
remarks: Final count day for Autumn 2012.  Our warm thanks to all the counters who could join us this year and help make this our best season yet!

observers: Simon Cavaillès, Giacomo Biasi, Rick Lockwood, Gabriel Caucal, Demain Hiss, Pia Fetting
remarks: Rather interesting first counting day with an unusal weather. Low clouds all the day long with some light rain, and a final thunderstorm that shortened the count.

observers: Simon Cavaillès, Giacomo Biasi, Albin Berglund, Gerd Wichers, Pia Fetting
remarks: Morning has been very calm, then Honey Buzzard started streaming in the afternoon. 17+1 Grey Herons seen, first Bee-eaters, some Ortolan Buntings and Short-toed Larks...

observers: Giacomo Biasi, Demian Hiss, Gabriel Caucal, Albin Berglund, Rick Lockwood, Pia Fetting
weather: mostly cloudy over the mountains, less to no clouds over the coast. warm and humid.

observers: Aki Aintila, Gabriel Caucal, Gerd Wichers, Bart Hoekstra
weather: sunny morning and nice migration with clear weather for afternoon

observers: Simon Cavaillès, Gabi E3 Caucal, Triin Kaasiku, Rick Lockwood, Gerd Wichers, Bart Hoekstra, Demian Hiss, Toukko sp
remarks: Rather calm day again, with loose streams of Honey Buzzards in the late afternoon. Definitely a slow season kick-off.2 Alpine Swifts, few passerines

observers: Aki Aintila, Giacomo Biasi, Albin Berglund, Gerd Wichers, Touko Torppa Pia Fetting, Triin Kaatuse
remarks: Some nice passage but a lot of Honey Buzzard migration hidden by clouds on east side of the watchpoint - we also picked up an adult Steppe Eagle and 2 Egyptian Vultures from Shuamta!

observers: Aki Aintila, Demian Hiss, Albin Berglund, Rick Lockwood, Gerd Wichers, Bart Hoekstra, Triin Kaasiku
remarks: Here we go! The first day of over 10 000 Honey Buzzards. Still relatively low numbers of harriers, but we had the first Roller of the season! Also nice views on Steppe Eagles with different age classes.

observers: Simon Cavaillès, Demian Hiss, John Wright, Triin Kaasiku, Gerd Wichers, Bart Hoekstra, Jonas Schärer
remarks: Harriers migration a bit more interesting today. Nice streams of Honey Buzzards, but still quite low numbers! A flock of 13 Night Herons in the morning.

observers: Aki Aintila, Rick Lockwood, John Wright, Bart Hoekstra, Touko Torpa, Gerd Wichers
remarks: Some thunder in the morning. During the first counting week we were stucked to 5.000 birds a day. We now reached the 10.000 bar and are stucked to it...Where are the birds?

observers: Simon Cavailles, Giacomo Biasi, Gerd Wichers, Gabi Caucal, Pia Fetting, Triin Kaasiku, Touko Torpa
remarks: Nice Honey Buzzards streams. More should come soon. Still waiting for the Rollers invasion!3 Glossy Ibises migrating along the coastline.

observers: Aki Aintila, Giacomo Biasi, John Wright, Gabriel Caucal, Rick Lockwood, Pia Fetting, Bart Hoekstra, Rei Seigali
weather: clear weather during the whole day
remarks: More and more Honey Buzzards coming in, over 47 000 today! Beautiful streams, huge flocks and close views on many birds, excellent atmosphere on the station during whole day. More to come hopefully...

observers: Simon Cavailles, Aki Aintila, John Wright, Gabriel Caucal, Demian Hiss, Albin Berglund, Pia Fetting
weather: clear weather during the whole day
remarks: The harrier and roller migration has started! Also nice migration of Honey Buzzards with the highest number of the season so far. Amazing!A few Grey Herons seen, 6 Ruddy Shelducks, 3 small Plovers in a flock of Turtle Doves.

observers: Aki Aintila, Simon Cavaillès, Gabi Caucal, Rick Lockwood, Pia Fetting, Albin Berglund, Demian Hiss, Gerd Wichers, Rei Segali
remarks: Very nice day on station 1, with interesting numbers and diversity. Massive Honey Buzzards migration ending up in a first migration peak for the species. We had some hectic hours in early afternoon. The main stream of birds was hitting the station at our level and exploding all around us. Hard time for counting, but so enjoyable!Very good migration of Harriers as well.Other species: 9 Glossy Ibises migrating along the coast

observers: Simon Cavailles, Aki Aintila, Albin Berglund, Rick Lockwood, Triin Kaasiku, Touko Torppa, Mike Jeanvoine, Doriane Hebinger
weather: cloudy morning and some rainshowers in the afternoon
remarks: Nice streams of Honey Buzzards and close views on some harriers. Flock of 30 pratincoles in the morning! More ecotourists start to arrive. After one rainshower, we heard calls of waders in the sky, a mixed flock of Wood Sandpipers and one call of Broad-billed Sandpiper!

observers: Aki Aintila, Simon Cavaillès, Albin Berglund, Bart Hoekstra, Triin Kaasiku, Rei Segali, Mike Jeanvoine, Doriane Hebinger
remarks: Observations started at mid-day because of heavy rain and thunderstorms. Few raptors migrating in a chaotic way, lots of shooting in the observation sphere.1st Common Rosefinch seen

observers: Aki Aintila, Giacomo Biasi, John Wright, Gerd Wichers, Triin Kaasiku, Touko Torppa, Mike Jeanvoine, Doriane Hebinger, Nick Gardner
remarks: Amazing day after yesterday's storms: +50 000 Honey Buzzard, first Crested Honey Buzzard of the season and a Dalmatian Pelican! The species diversity is increasing with more harriers, Ospreys and Booted Eagles.

observers: Simon Cavailles, Giacomo Biasi, Albin Berglund, Gerd Wichers, Touko Torppa, John Wright, Rei Seigali, Nick Gardner
remarks: Cloudy; short rain shower in the afternoon.Very nice migration day, we enjoyed the numbers of rollers and turtle doves crossing the sky. We had many close birds and we've been able to spot two Crested Honey Buzzard soaring with European HBs.The weather conditions made the birds fly mostly low. That, unfortunately, was accompanied by many shots.

observers: Simon Cavaillès, Aki Aintila, Touko Torppa, Baastian de Ketelaere, Thomas Cansee, Gerd Wichers, Rei Segali, Ruben Vernieuwe, Mike Jeanvoine, Doriane Hebinger, Nick Gardner, Andy Francis, Dachi
remarks: Rainy day with weak migration. Thunderstorms pushed us downhill back and forth.

observers: Albin Berglund, Demian Hiss, Gabriel Caucal, Giacomo Biasi, John Wright, Triin Kaasiku
remarks: Good exercise today: the rainy weather made us go up and down from the viewpoint several times. It was impressive to see the raptors take advantage of the breaks in the rain to keep on traveling. Many birds offered us good close up views and some landed on trees in front of us. Special thanks to Triin for mending the cover of our shelter.

observers: Aki Aintila, Simon Cavaillès, Mike Jeanvoine, Doriane Hebinger, Gabi Caucal, Ruben Vernieuwe, Thomas Cansse, Dachi Shoshitashvili, Gerd Wichers, Demian Hiss
remarks: Good migration day with interesting species diversity and lots of close views. Still very low numbers of Pallid and Montagu's Harriers though.

observers: Aki Aintila, Gaby Caucal, Rei Segali, Mike Jeanvoine, Doriane Hebinger, Nick Gardner, Andrew Francis, Bastiaan, De Ketelaere, Valentin Moser, Levon Harytunyan, Jani Vastamäki
Simon Cavailles, Aki Aintila, Demian Hiss, Gaby Caucal, Gerd Wichers, Nick Gardner, Andrew Francis, Thomas Cansse, Valentin Moser, Levon Haryunyan, Jani Vastamäki, Romain Legnagne
Aki Aintila, Demian Hiss, Gabriel Caucal, Gerd Wichers, Rei Segali, Mike Jeanvoine, Doriane Hebinger, Andrew Francis, Jani Vastamäki, Roman Lengagne
remarks: The raptor migration is getting diverse and diverse! Very good harrier migration in the morning but also in the evening, interesting number of Pallid Harriers.

observers: Aki Aintila, Gabriel Caucal, Albin Berglund, John Wright, Rei Segali, Thomas Cansse, Levon Harytunyan, Romain Legnagne, Jidde Spangenberg
weather: Clear weather during the whole day
remarks: Very good harrier migration with more than 250 harriers migrating during the first hours of the day! Increasing totals of Booted Eagles and Black Kites, we are heading to the most diverse phase of the season!

observers: Albin Berglund, Giacomo Biasi, Valentin Moser, Demian Hiss, Jidde Spanderberg, Doriane Hebinger, Mike Jeanvoine, Jani Vastamaki, John Wright, Adrien Brun, Dachi Shoshitashvili
remarks: Quiet but nice day, with a good number of Booted Eagles, Short toed Eagles, Ospreys and Harriers. It has been a good migration for Hobbies too and we spotted also a few Common Kestrels. In the late morning we welcomed our new coordinator, Adrien from France, who stayed on the station until sunset despite the long journey. A magnificent sunset on the Black Sea was the perfect conclusion to our day.

observers: Aki Aintila, Adrien Brun, John Wright, Albin Berglund, Gerd Wichers, Mike Jeanvoine, Doriane Hebinger, Levon Harytunyan, Jidde Spangenberg
remarks: Excellent Black Kite migration on both count stations! The harriers kept us busy in the morning with over 200 birds in first hours of the day, also nice migration of Booted Eagles!

observers: Jani Vastamäki, Andrew Fancis, Gerd Wichers, Basstiaan De Ketelaere, Demian Hiss, Ruben Verniuwe, Valentin Moser, Thomas Cansse, Adrien Brun, Giacomo Biasi, Philippe Malenfert
remarks: Quiet day on Station 1 - Sakhalvasho. Despite the few birds counted, we had good time. We could spend more time observing the harriers crossing close to us, mostly juveniles Montagu´s and a few Pallid. Gorgeous birds!

observers: Adrien Brun, Aki Aintila, John Wright, Albin Berglund, Ruben Verniuwe, Thomas Cansse, Bastiaan de Ketelaere, Jidde Spangenberg, Philippe Malenfert
remarks: After a slow morning we had some nice migration in the afternoon with mixed flocks of Black Kites, Honey Buzzards and Steppe Buzzards!

observers: Gabi Caucal, Albin Berglund, Giacomo Biasi, Demian Hiss, John Wright, Romain Lengagne, Thomas Cansse, Ruben Vernieuwe, Philippe Malenfert, Nick Gardner
remarks: Quite a good day for Booted Eagles on Station 1. Migrating mixed flocks of Black Kites, Honey Buzzards and Steppe Buzzards challenged our counters by spreading and mixing along the transect line. The communication between the two stations and the dedication of the counters have been essential to keep the count under control. Good practice for the peak period of the Steppe Buzzards!

observers: Giacomo Biasi, Adrien Brun, Gabi E3 Caucal, John Wright, Levon Harutyunyan, Jidde Spangerberg, Romain Lengagne, Philippe Malenfert, Valentijn Van Bergen
remarks: Clouds and rain provided a strange but interesting day of migration. Not many raptors but in close view and we took good pics of juveniles Black Kites and Montagu's Harriers. Some Ospreys crossed close by, too. Even some Shovelers popped in our binoculars. Looking over the sea we had some interesting spotting: a big flock of Ruffs flying in an elegant line formation; a big flock of Marsh Terns; and Arctic Skuas. Yeah baby!

observers: Adrien Brun, Demian Hiss, Gabriel Caucal, John Wright, Bastiaan de Ketelaere, Valentin Moser, Romain Legnange, Valentijn van Bergen
Adrien Brun, John Wright, Bastiaan De Ketelaere, Philippe Malenfert, Bernard Siddle, Carole Davis, Matthias Kellerman
remarks: Amazing day of migration after several days of strom and rain. More than 70 000 birds counted by the two stations teams all day long!!! Breaking of the black kites day record! Also an amazing day for the booted eagles. And this fantastic observation of a young saker falcon very close from the station.

observers: Adrien Brun, John Wright, Bastiaan De Ketelaere, Philippe Malenfert, Bernard Siddle, Carole Davis, Matthias Kellerman
remarks: After the amazing day we still had nice flocks of Booted Eagles all morning long with Levant Sparrowhawks always visible in the surroundings and two very nice observations of Greater Spotted Eagles. One of them was a beautiful juvenile with an all gingerish body. Steady weather with cool temperature following the storms of these last days. Fantastic visibility on the snowy great Caucasus and the Elbrus mount.

observers: Adrien Brun, Folkert de Boer, Filiep T'jollyn, Jani Vastamäki, Jidde Spangenberg , Bernard Siddle, Carole Davis, Matthias Kellerman
remarks: Rather quiet day with nice close observations of birds like this Red-footed Falcon male soaring in front of the station or mixed flocks of Honey Buzzards and Booted Eagles. Steady warm weather without wind.

observers: Aki Aintilla, John Wright, Bastiaan De Ketelaere, Romain Lengagne, Matthias Kellerman
remarks: extremely warm day, +32 degrees in the shade! still the birds were coming in really low, apparently there were no proper thermals. Never mind the low numbers, the diversity of species was still great.

observers: Aki Aintila, John Wright, Philippe Malenfert, Romain Lengagne
remarks: Extremely slow morning with rainy midday and afternoon. But, slow days and weather like this can mean only one thing, we will have a good day soon!

observers: Giacomo Biasi, Aki Aintila, Demian Hiss, Gabriel Caucal, Bernard Siddle, Pia Fetting
remarks: Really slow day again, low clouds and light rain showers most of the day. Where are the birds?
No observations because of bad weather.

observers: Adrien Brun, Giacomo Biasi, Filiep T'Jollyn, John W3 Wright, Demian Hiss, Bernard Siddle, Andreas Wiedenmann, Frauke Helms, Diego Jansen, Dries Engelen, Anna Sandor, Guillaume Peplinski
remarks: Red-Footed Falcon day in Sakhalvasho! This is the best day since we have included the RFFs in the count (the unofficial record is of about 700 birds in 2013). Also other small falcons were very abundant with many hobbies and kestrels passing the station, and even some lesser kestrels.It was also a decent day for Pallid Harriers, which finally seem to be coming through! And they offered us nice views and nice photos. Furthermore a group of 19 spoonbills and 14 night herons in the early morning.

observers: Giacomo Biasi, Adrien Brun, Dries Engelen, Gabi Caucal, Valentijn van Bergen, Carole Davis, Matthias Kellerman, Will Salmon, Andreas Wiedenmann, Frauke Helms
remarks: Another very nice day for the red-foted falcons with several very close observations of flocks around the counters. More black kites coming until late in the evening, probably an introduction for tomorrow. The day ended with two nice flocks of black storks in the evening light.First stock dove of the season and a long-legged buzzard!

observers: Adrien Brun, Dries Engelen, Filiep T'jollyn, Demian Hiss, Matthias Kellerman, Will Salmon, Andreas Wiedenmann, Frauke Helms, Anna Sandor
remarks: Today was the black kites day. From the very first hour of counting to the end of the day, we had a stream going on with huge flocks very low overhead. After the recent breaking of the daily we are now heading for the season record, like the four previous year. THE observation of the day : an amazing kettle of 140 EAGLES!!!!A crazy afternoon for all the counters who did a very good team work. Well done!

observers: Dries Engelen, Carole Davis, Bernard Siddle, John Wright, Diego Jansen, Ivo Tonev, Olga Lukshyts, Rien van Wijk, Filiep T'Jollyn
remarks: It was raining more or less the entire day, and even though the views were pretty good, the birds seemed to prefer Station-2 today. One cuckoo however decided to pass our station and did so by first nearly flying into Bernard (who was the only counter not seeing the bird) and after that it could just avoid our shelter by less than a meter.

observers: Aki Aintila, Demian Hiss, John Wright, Guillaume Peplinski, Valentijn van Bergen, Rien van Wijk, Andreas Wiedenmann, Olga Lukshyts, Ivalyo Tonev
weather: heavy showers all day and some sun in between
remarks: Excellent migration despite the unstable weather. Again an excellent day for Red-footed Falcons and harriers!

observers: Adrien Brun, Dries Engelen, John Wright, Matthias Kellerman, Frauke Helms, Romain Lengagne, Will Salmon, Vedran Lucic, Eva Knizatkova
remarks: Even though the numbers on station 1 are much lower than in Shuamta, we had an incredible day of migration with some of the best views of birds this season. Especially the number of male pallid harriers and the flock of more than 300 red-footed falcons were impressive and left all counters in awe. The southern wind made the birds move very slow and we had plenty of time to watch them, unfortunately so did the hunters.

observers: Dries Engelen, Diego Jansen, Aki Aintila, Filiep T'Jollyn, Bernard Siddle, Carole Davis, Matthias Kellerman, Romain Lengagne, Eva Knizatkova, Vedran Lucic, Ivo Tonev, Valentijn van Bergen, Anton Christiaens
remarks: Finally a day with fully blue skies again and great views on the Caucasus mountains. We had a 2000 Black Kite stream in the west directly in the morning which made us pass the 150.000 Black Kites this season, destroying the former record by more than 20.000 birds! Good migration during the rest of the day too with nice variety and 5 Steppe Eagles until things calmed down during the last 2 hours. Next days should be sunny too, so stay tuned because we are approaching the million!

observers: Aki Aintila, Adrien Brun, Gabriel Caucal, Romain Lengagne, Rien van Wijk, Andreas Wiedenmann, Frauke Helms, Olga Lukshyts, Vedran Lucic,
remarks: Extrelemy enjoyable migration during most of the day! Black Kites keep on coming bringing along lots of goodies, like 6 Greater Spotted and 8 Steppe Eagles. Other highlights were the first Crane of the season, a late Roller, flocks of Red-Footed Falcons and Lesser Kestrels and also interesting and diverse passerine migration in the early morning, incl. 8 Red-Throated Pipits, Water Pipit, 17 Calandra Larks and Corn Buntings.

observers: Giacomo Biasi, Filiep T'Jollin, Eva Knizatkova, John Wright, Rien van Wijk, Ivo Tonev, Aki Aintila, Matthias Kellerman, Olga Lukshyts,
remarks: Black Kites seem endless this year! We keep counting streams of them. Very disciplined streams compared to the Steppe Buzzards who like to linger for ages and splitting and rejoining and join some other kettle before streaming off.During the morning with clear sky we could see a clear separation in the preferred track for these two species: Black Kites were passing closer to the coast and we were counting them at Sakhalvasho, whereas Steppe Buzzards were passing over the hills in the East, being counted by Station 2.in the afternoon clouds covered the hills and pushed the Eagles to the West. During some minutes we had Eagles overhead, with a good number of Greater Spotteds. A gorgeous juvenile in the afternoon light was the happy ending of the day.

observers: Dries Engelen, Giacomo Biasi, Gabi Caucal, Demian Hiss, Rien van Wijk, Romain Lengagne, Ivo Tonev, Eva Knizatkova, Vedran Lucic
remarks: Incredible eagle day, not much more to add... :D Some streams were made up of more eagles than any other birds. The raptors also followed protocol as the last big stream finished exactly one minute before the end of the official count.

observers: Dries Engelen, Giacomo Biasi, Gabi Caucal, Diego Jansen, Valentijn van Bergen, Guillaume Peplinski, Vedran Lucic, Frauke Helms,
remarks: The morning started calm so we had to wait a few hours before we reached the 1 million! While popping the champagne bottles we had a very nice sight of a merlin circling for some minutes over the station. Then  things really kicked off with another great day of eagle migration. We had a juvenile Imperial, juvenile Steppe and a juvenile Greater Spotted all in the same scope view. Other highlights were the overhead stream of Short-toed Eagles, the overhead immature Imperial eagle and the juvenile Griffon Vulture in our close east. All in all a great day to celebrate the 5th consecutive year of 1 million raptors!

observers: Aki Aintila, Gabriel Caucal, Filiep T'jollyn, Diego Jansen, Will Salmon, Olga Lukshyts, Adreas Wiedenmann, Frauke Helms
remarks: What a day! It all seemed to start as a quiet one, but after a short wait we started to get nice flocks of harriers all around the station, and eventually we counted more than 100 Marsh Harriers and 12 Pallid Harriers within the first two hours! After the harriers we started to get more eagles and Steppe Buzzards, with still relatively many Black Kites moving on. Even though the numbers were not that overwhelming, the diverse migration and scattered streams kept us busy. We still have 10 days to go and lots of more birds to come!

observers: Giacomo Biasi, Demian Hiss, John Wright, Romain Lengagne, Olga Lukshyts, Ivo Tonev
remarks: A nice afternoon today, with a good number of eagles in an enjoyable view. In particular we will remember two birds: a beautiful, very pale juvenile Lesser Spotted Eagle, who circled overhead; and an adult Eastern Imperial Eagle soaring in a good light.We also enjoyed a surprising view in the morning: some clouds in the East, low on the horizon, were lit by the morning sun and the refracted light picted them with iris colours. It looked like mother-of-pearl hanging in the sky. Stunning.

observers: Giacomo Biasi, John Wright, Andreas Wiedenmann, Frauke Helms, Ivo Tonev, Diego Jansen, Eva Knizatkova
remarks: A quiet day for migration, but we still had some nice eagles. The highlight of the day is a flock of 240 rooks that streamed in front of the sea.

observers: Giacomo Biasi, Aki Aintila, John Wright, Filiep T'jollyn, Demian Hiss, Romain Lengagne, Olga Lukshyts
remarks: Extremely quiet morning and midday, around 15:00 we had a rain shower and after that things started to happen! Within the last 2 hours of the day we saw more than 117 Kestrels migrating south, along with +30 Red-Footed Falcons, some Hobbies and the odd Lesser Kestrels. We also saw a Black Stork, Steppe Eagle, Short-toed Eagle, Osprey - and really nice Pallid Harriers! Still 7 days to go...

observers: Aki Aintila, Giacomo Biasi, Demian Hiss, Romain Lengagne, Vedran Lucic, Eva Knizetkova, Jan Ranson
weather: rainy morning with low visibility, early afternoon the weather cleared and we managed to count some birds

observers: Dries Engelen, Gabi Caucal, Diego Jansen, Frauke Helms, Andreas Wiedenmann, Eva Knizatkova, Vedran Lucic
remarks: Hardly any birds for most of the day, but we kept ourselves sharp by doing some jumprope excercises (very good for the team spirit!). This way we could properly deal with the messy stream situation between the 2 stations for the last 1.5 hours of the count.

observers: Dries Engelen, Aki Aintila, John Wright, Diego Jansen, Ivo Tonev, Vedran Lucic
remarks: Another calm day for our count station. Nice variation though with an adult white-tailed eagle and a near-fulvescens juvenile greater spotted. Also a big flock of 60 black storks and 5 (very late) white storks was a nice sight!

observers: Giacomo Biasi, Demian Hiss, Gabi Caucal, Ivo Tonev, Jan Ranson, Dries Engelen
remarks: Although good weather was forecasted, we ended up with a windy day with several showers and few birds. The last half hour things cleared up and we had close views of a male and female red-breasted flycatcher perched in a tree in front of us. Now its time to enjoy the evening sun with a swim!

observers: Giacomo Biasi, Gabi Caucal, John Wright, Ivo Tonev, Jan Ranson, Romain Lengagne
remarks: Bad weather.... we gave it a try, but there were not many birds around.

observers: Gaby E15 Caucal, Romain Lengagne, Giacomo Biasi, Demian Hiss, John Wright, Jan Ranson, Diego Jansen
remarks: Bad weather again, but in the afternoon some nice observation rewarded our patience: a male Hen Harrier, several Pallids and a juvenile Peregrine in close view.One day left and still we want more birds to count!

observers: Giacomo Biasi, John Wright, Romain Lengagne, Ivaylo Tonev, Olga Lukshyts
remarks: The last day of the count. We hit 180,000 Black Kites today! It was good to see some Pallid Harriers, an Osprey, the migration of Mistle and Song Thrushes, Chaffinches, Bramblings, Woodlarks...And it was good to spend the last hours with storytelling, jokes and lots, lots of laughs. Thanks to all the people involved in this edition of the count!

remarks: Local raptors: 1 juv Goshawk, 1 Peregrine FalconOther local birds: Thrush Nightingale, Raven, Black Woodpecker, ...Passerine migration: 2 Black-headed Bunting, some Tree Pipits, Ortolan Buntings, Lesser Grey Shrike

observers: Jasper Wehrmann, Marta Per(n)is Cabre, Mael Sinoir, Nicolas Vanderstraten
remarks: some migration of passerines with a group of Bee-eaters, a Red-breasted Flycatcher, Tree Pipits, an Ortolan and a few Lesser Grey Shrikes...

observers: Arthur Green, Mael Sinoir, Nicolas Vanderstrate, Michael Olofsson
remarks: Quiet day with 6 Ortolan Buntings, a flock of Bee-eaters.local raptors : a Goshawk

observers: Arthur Green, Mael Sinoir, Nicolas Vanderstrate, Linus Hedh
remarks: local birds: Goshawk, WHITE BACKED WOODPECKER, Black Woodpecker, passerine migration: some Bee-eater flocks, Alpine Swifts ...

observers: Nicolas Vanderstraten, Marta Peris Cabre, Simon Cavailles, Farzaneh Etezadifar, Pim Wolf
remarks: remark: 1 Large Falcon spec.: most likely a calidus Peregrine. Pics available for confirmation.

observers: Mael Sinoir, Arthur Green, Michael Olofsson, Klas Rosenkvist,
Maël Sinoir, Arthur Green, Nicolas Vanderstrate, Ahmad Barati, Linus Hedh
remarks: Flocks of Tree Pipit, Alpine Swift, Bee-eaters, (local) Northern Goshawk, (non-migrating) Long-legged Buzzard.

observers: Simon Cavaillès, Pim Wolf, Jasper Wehrmann, Raul Vicente, Ahmad  Barati, Farzaneh Etezadifar
remarks: Strong Ortolan Buntings migration (85 with a flock of 25+ birds), 23 Tree Pipits, 15 Bee-eaters...

remarks: the clouds and rain directed most of the migration to the coast

observers: Simon Cavailles, Giacomo Biasi, Demian Hiss, Pia Fetting
remarks: Calm and sunny morning, low clouds in the afternoon and drizzle to finish with. Nice waders migration: 1 Grey Plover heard, 12+10+16 Ruffs

observers: Aki Aintila, Giacomo Biasi, Albin Berglund, Pia Fetting
weather: again a sunny morning but cloudy afternoon
remarks: we start to see signs of harrier migratien (where are they!?), also some nice Honey Buzzard streams in late afternoon

observers: Simon Cavaillès, Rick Lockwood, Bart Hoekstra, Gabriel Caucal
remarks: Very slow start today, with nice migration going on in the late afternoon. Several highlights: 2 Egyptian Vultures, an adult Steppe Eagle and 4 Arctic Skuas flying in front of a stream of Honey Buzzards and soaring above the Ridge. All dark morphs.

observers: Simon Cavaillès, Gerd Wichers, Demian Hiss, Triin Kaasiku
remarks: Cloudy afternoon, late streams of Honey Buzzards again. Nice eagle day with our first Lesser Spotted Eagle, then a group of 3 adults Steppe Eagle soaring during long minutes.Where are the harriers?

observers: Simon Cavaillès, Gabi Caucal, Pia Fetting, Touko Torpa
remarks: Nice migration day with decent Honey Buzzards streams. First season Roller. Steppe Eagles continue to keep counters excited.All Honey Buzzards counted from station 1

observers: Aki Aintila, Giacomo Biasi, Gabriel Caucal, Pia Fetting, Albin Berglund
remarks: Nice flocks and an adult Steppe Eagle in our east side during the early day, later most of the birds went along the coast.

observers: Giacomo Biasi, Gabriel Caucal, Pia Fetting, Albin Berglund, Demian Hiss, Jonas Schärer
remarks: Some nice passerines kept counters awoken during this slow migration day: Ortolan Buntings, Tree Pipits, Whinchat, Marsh Warbler, Hawfinch...

observers: Aki Aintila, Demian Hiss, Albin Berglund, John Wright, Bart Hoekstra, Rick Lockwood
weather: clear weather during the whole day
remarks: Great fun on Station2 today! Nice passage of birds overhead and both sides of the station (most counted by Station1), pure enjoyment of Honey Buzzard migration!

observers: Simon Cavaillès, Demian Towers, Albin Berglund, Touko Torpa, Triin Kaasiku, Gerd Wichers
remarks: Very nice migration of Honey Buzzards, with constant large stream(s) towards the coast. Very few other species otherwise.All Honey Buzzards counted from station 1.

observers: Giacomo Biasi, Triin Kaasiku, Touko Torpa, Rei Segali, Gerd Wichers
Giacomo Biasi, Triin Kaasiku, Touko Torpa, Rei Segali, Gerd Wichers
Giacomo Biasi, John Wright, Bart Hoekstra, Triin Kaasuke, Touko Torppa
remarks: Insane harrier migration!Honey Buzzards counted from station 1

observers: Giacomo Biasi, John Wright, Rei Segali, Gerd Wichers, Demian Hiss, Bart Hoekstra
remarks: Strong Bee-eaters migration, interesting numbers of Short-toel Larks as well

observers: Simon Cavaillès, Gabi E3 Caucal, Demian Hiss, Rei Segali, Albin Berglund
remarks: Very enjoyable couting day, with important Harriers and Honey Buzzard migration. Diversity clearly more important than previous days. 4 dark morph Marsh Harriers seen today.First team observation of Red-breasted Flycatcher, a flock of 13 Ruffs, and 10 Shuddy Relducks.

observers: Aki Aintila, Gabriel Caucal, Demian Hiss, Triin Kaasuke, Mike Jeanvoine, Doriane Hebinger
remarks: The harriers kept us busy during the morning. After the Honey Buzzard migration started, we had light pours of rain bringing the birds down; really enjoyable views on hundreds of Honey Buzzards on close eye-level!

observers: Albin Berglund, Giacomo Biasi, Bastiaan De Ketelaere, Nick Gardner, John Wright
remarks: The morning was dotted with honey buzzards and black kites leaving their roosts after the thunderstorm, and we observed a steady passage in the good weather during the day. The proportion of black kites and levant is increasing. It was nice to see a few Eagles and some good view of juveniles Montagu's Harriers. Overall a good day with good people on the station.

observers: Simon Cavaillès, John Wright, Albin Berglund, Gerd Wichers, Ruben Vernieuwe, Thomas Cansse
remarks: Very enjoyable day with close streams and good birds. Some Crested Honey Buzzards including a putative female hybrid, large Eagles, Harriers and others. We are getting close to the Booted Eagle peak day.

observers: Albin Berglund, Giacomo Biasi, Bastiaan De Ketelaere, Ruben Verniuwe, John Wright, Dachi
remarks: Nice weather made the birds fly high, but still we could have done good view on overhead Ospreys and a few Egyptian Vultures mixing up with the Honey Buzzards.

observers: Giacomo Biasi, Thomas Cansse, Bastiaan De Ketelaere, Nick Gardner, Valentin Moser, Ruben Verniuwe
remarks: High flying harriers made our day, filling the morning and evening sky with their elegant appearance. We enjoyed a very good and cheerful atmosphere on the field and we would like to thanks three ecotourist birders who helped us in picking some birds up.

observers: Giacomo Biasi, Gerd Wichers, Bastiaan De Ketelaere, Ruben Verniuwe, Doriane Hebinger, Mike Jeanvoine, Andrew Francis, Jani Vastamäki
remarks: Good day of count, quite busy with harriers. It´s interesting to see the changes in the migration: steppe buzzards start to mix up with the honey buzzards, we are able to see more pallid harriers, large eagles are now a constant presence.

observers: Aki Aintila, Gaby Caucal, Gerd Wichers, Nick Gardner, Ruben Verniuwe, Thomas Cansse, Baastian de Ketelaere, Levon Harytunyan, Romain Legnagne,
remarks: Nice migration with diverse species, 2 Egyptians and more Lesser Spotted Eagles!

observers: Aki Aintila, Gaby Caucal, Albin Berglund, John Wright, Nick Gardner, Thomas Cansse, Romain Legnagne, Jidde Spangenberg
weather: blue sky all along and almost no cloud coverage
remarks: Birds migrating mostly high up in the sky, still some enjoyable views on nice streams. Also a group of 6 Ruddy Shelducks!

observers: Giacomo Biasi, Gabi Caucal, Demian Hiss, Andrew Francis, Valentin Moser, Romain Lengagne, Levon Harytunyan, Nick Gardner
remarks: Today has been a good day with mixed flocks of Honey Buzzards, Steppe Buzzards and Black Kites. In the afternoon we had very close birds and beautiful juveniles honeys and steppes in beautiful light.

observers: Aki Aintila, Adrien Brun, Gerd Wichers, Andrew Francis, Bastiaan de Ketelaere, Valentin Moser, Levon Harytunyan, Jani Vastamäki, Jidde Spangengberg
Giacomo Biasi, Filiep T'jollyn, Gerd Wichers, Ruben Verniuwe, Thomas Cansse, Levon Harytunyan, Jani Vastamäki, Philippe Malenfert,
Giacomo Biasi, Filiep T'jollyn, Gabi Caucal, Jani Vastamäki, Romain Lengagne, Jidde Spangenberg, Philippe Malenfert
remarks: Very good day of migration! We've been busy counting all day long. A good number of Short-toed and Lesser Spoted Eagles. A very good team made the count possible. Thank you guys!

observers: Aki Aintila, Filiep T'jollyn, Demian Hiss, Gabriel Caucal, Jani Vastamäki, Levon Harytunyan, Jidde Spangenberg, Valentijn van Bergen
Aki Aintila, Demian Hiss, John Wright, Gabriel Caucal, Bastiaan de Ketelaere, Romain Legnange, Philippe Malenfert, Valentijn Van Bergen
weather: blue skies and no clouds at all during the day
remarks: slow migration after excellent two days, but still really nice species composition!

observers: Giacomo Biasi, Demian Hiss, Gabi Caucal, Philippe Malenfert, Bernard Siddle, Carole Davis
remarks: Quiet day, with high temperature and clear sky. Good people made the day, despite there were few birds to count. Highlight of the day: a 2nd cy white tailed eagle flying low in our west side. Probably a local bird.

observers: Adrien Brun, Gabi Caucal, Giacomo Biasi, Bernard Siddle, Carole Davis,
remarks: Today the bad weather blocked the migration and we counted very few birds. A juvenile Black Kite teased us crossing the transact line in both S and N direction several times. A thunderstorm made us leave the station and rain was there all day long. A good chance to rest, all in all.

observers: Giacomo Biasi, Valentijn van Bergen, John Wright, Romain Lengagne, Demian Hiss, Philippe Malenfert, Bernard Siddle
remarks: The Eagles are there. We are still waiting for a good day of migration, but we had a promising passage of Eagles today. They are waiting for a better weather. And so we are. We expect a big big day, and we are ready!
No observations because of bad weather.

observers: Aki Aintila, Gabriel Caucal, Romain Lengagne, Philippe Malenfert, Valentijn van Bergen, Carole Davis, Rien van Wijk, Pia Fetting
weather: very cloudy, many rainshowers during the day
remarks: The migration is starting again! Despite the unstaible weather, the birds had much clearer passage than previous days and the migration was diverse as ever! Today we observed 18 different raptor species! And there's more to come...

observers: Aki Aintila, Filiep T'jollyn, Demian Hiss, John Wright, Romain Lengagne, Bernard Siddle, Rien van Wijk, Diego Jansen
remarks: More birds finally! After many rainy and unstable days the skies cleared and the counting team was sweating with streams. Another epic day for Black Kites, also excellent migration for Lesser Spotted Eagles with some nice treats, like Egyptian Vultures and Peregrine Falcons along the way. Looking forward to see more birds tomorrow!

observers: Aki Aintila, Giacomo Biasi, John Wright, Gabriel Caucal, Romain Lengagne, Valentijn van Bergen, Guillaume Peplinski, Bernard Siddle, Carole Davis, Diego Jansen, Pia Fetting, Rien van Wijk
remarks: Busy morning after yesterday, counting big flocks of Black Kites on both sides of the station. The early afternoon was a bit quiet, but after 16:00 we started to see more and more eagles. First in fixed streams, but after 16:30 - BOOM! Eagles all around, in streams and flocks, during the trickiest moments we had many flocks of +100 eagles visible at the same time! Station 2 surrounded by eagles! I close my eyes and I see eagles! EAGLES!

observers: Giacomo Biasi, Adrien Brun, Demian Hiss, Gabi Caucal, Romain Lengagne, Valentijn van Bergen, Matthias Kellerman, Will Salmon, Andreas Wiedenmann, Frauke Helms
remarks: A hard but very impressive counting day for the team! Almost 20 000 raptors counted under the rain and in the wind. The morning was quiet then a wall of steppe buzzards arrives on the east in early afternoon. Then this huge stream never stopped until almost the end of the count, when the wind got stonger. In this stream there were also almost 500 eagles, among which several close to the station like those two juveniles greater spotted.

observers: Adrien Brun, Dries Engelen, Filiep T'jollyn, Gabi Caucal, Bernard Siddle, Carole Davis, Matthias Kellerman, Will Salmon, Diego Jansen
remarks: Nice migration on station two today. Unfortunately many interruptions because of the rain. But between the showers appeared streams of steppe buzzards, marsh harriers and eagles. Several nice observations of close birds : lesser spotted eagles, male of pallid harrier, botted eagles. Once again, tough but very good job done by the counters!

observers: Aki Aintila, Giacomo Biasi, Demian Hiss, Gabriel Caucal, Diego Jansen, Guillaume Peplinski, Rien van Wijk, Ivaylo Tonev, Olga Lukshyts, Bernard Siddle, Carole Davis
weather: constant rain and hard wind most of the day, clear weather late afternoon
remarks: Again heavy migration under difficult weather conditions! Hundreds of Steppe Buzzards pushing through in wind and rain, accompanied by harriers and eagles. Around 15:30, when the rain stopped, we suddenly were overwhelmed by birds and counted more than 25000 Steppe Buzzards in less than two hours! The whole team were doing amazing job, thank you all!

observers: Giacomo Biasi, Adrien Brun, Demian Hiss, Gabi Caucal, John Wright, Will Salmon, Rien van Wijk, Andreas Wiedenmann, Frauke Helms, Volha Lukshyts,
remarks: After days of cold weather, we were eventually able to count under a shining sun that brought us an amazing day on station two! Streams since the very first hour of counting, a wall of birds the all afternoon on the east side, mainly Steppe Buzzards, and a horizon full of coming birds. A lot of others species with for example the fifth best number ever on Batumi for Black Storks (a flock of 91!). This was the quantity, but we also had the quality with this adult male of Crested Honey Buzzard, those Long-legged buzzards in front of the station, those two Griffon Vulture and eagles. Eagles! A juvenile Steppe Eagle wandering few tens of meters from the station and two beautiful juveniles of Imperial Eagles crossing just in front of us!

observers: Dries Engelen, Giacomo Biasi, Valentijn Van Bergen, Diego Jansen, John Wright, Filiep T'jollyn, Eva Knizatkova, Ivo Tonev, Matthias Kellerman, Guillaume Peplinski
remarks: Slowish migration in very hazy weather with 3 juvenile steppe eagles together in a kettle and a flock of 41 black_e_storks as the highlights of the day.

observers: Dries Engelen, Gabi Caucal, Diego Jansen, Valentijn van Bergen, Frauke Helms, Andreas Wiedenmann, Vedran Lucic, Will Salmon, Romain Lengagne, Demian Hiss
remarks: The morning started very calm, but we had a flock of 12 Ruddy Shelducks overhead and a stout (or marten, still dicussing it) and dormouse on station to keep us entertained. Then migration picked up and larg numbers of eagles came through with the imperial and a very pale immature steppe eagle as the highlights. The day ended with 15 short-toed eagles coming down from the sky within 5 minutes of each other to search for a roosting place.

observers: Aki Aintila, John Wright, Filiep T'jollyn, Valentijn van Bergen, Diego Jansen, Will Salmon, Olga Lukshyts, Matthias Kellerman
remarks: Nice day for eagles, beautiful juv fulvescens Greater Spotted as the clear highlight. Looking forward to see more!

observers: Aki Aintila, John Wright, Demian Hiss, Romain Lengagne, Rien van Vijk, Eva Knizatkova, Olga Lukshyts, Ivo Tonev, Matthias Kellerman
remarks: Excellent eagle migration! Highlights were ADULT IMPERIAL EAGLE (+2juv and 1 imm), amazing diversity of different Greater Spotted Eagle plumages and great views on other species as well. It's a Batumi Eagle Feast!Also, today was the day when we - yet again - reached a total of 1 MILLION RAPTORS! Huge thanks to all the volunteers, members of the project and our supporters!

observers: Dries Engelen, Giacomo Biasi, John Wright, Vedran Lucic, Eva Knizatkova, Demian Hiss, Romain Lengagne
remarks: More clouded than last days, but still a nice variety of species and a good number of steppe buzzards (although several gloopsed in the clouds). At some points the streams were very broad but the team worked well together and the atmosphere was very nice today.

observers: Aki Aintila, Filiep T'jollyn, Gabriel Caucal, Diego Jansen, Andreas Wiedenmann, Frauke Helms, Will Salmon
weather: heavy clouds over the station but no rain
remarks: Some migration on the east side early in the day, but most of the birds migrated closer to the coast to evade the clouds. Highlights were on ad male Pallid passing really close, almsot hitting the station, the Imperial Eagles and a close juvenile Hen Harrier.

observers: Dries engelen, Aki aintila, Filiep t'jollyn, vedran lucic, Olga lukshyts, Valentijn 'grylls' van bergen
remarks: Quite a hazy day in which birds found it difficult to find good thermals, which resulted in slow migration. Highlight was definitely the 2 Krueper's nuthatches visiting our count station.

observers: Dries Engelen, Diego Jansen, Eva Knizatkova, Vedran Lucic, Ivo Tonev, Gabi Caucal
remarks: Last 2 hours we were gloopsed in the clouds. Just before that happened, many marsh harriers started dropping from the clouds. Other than that a very calm day with still surprisingly many bee-eaters for this time of the season. Also increasing numbers of chaffinches.

observers: Dries Engelen, Gabi Caucal, Diego Jansen, Frauke Helms, Andreas Wiedenmann, Ivo Tonev
remarks: Three hours of zero visibilty and constant light rain, so we decided to call it a day. The only birds around were 1 kestrel, 1 hobby, 1 chiffchaff and 1 wren.

observers: Aki Aintila, Giacomo Biasi, John Wright, Demian Hiss, Romain Lengagne, Jan Ranson, Olga Lukshyts, Ivo Tonev
remarks: Now this was worth the wait! After two slow days the skies cleared again and almost immediately we witnessed Steppe Buzzards coming up on the northern hills. Unfortunately, most of the migration until early afternoon was counting MUIDs in far east, since the birds passed further away without cloud coverage. Than the clouds came in, and after an hour of waiting, the first birds started to head our overhead and suddenly we were in the middle of migrating raptors! Juv Imperial Eagle, Greater Spotteds of many age classes, 2 Peregrines, 2 Merlins, and again a nice day for Long-legged Buzzards.

observers: Aki Aintila, John Wright, Romain Lengagne, Diego Jansen, Olga Lukshyts, Vedran Lucic
weather: many rain showers in the morning, but clear weather during the late afternoon
remarks: rain and wind messing up the count most of the day, but in the afternoon we counted a far stream of SB's in the east and enjoyed a few Greater Spotted Eagles, beauties...
Rainy, foggy and windy... no count on station 2 today!
Again a rainy day with very poor visibility, so we only counted some time from station 1 today.

observers: Dries Engelen, Aki Aintila, Gabi Caucal, Demain Hiss, Diego Jansen, Jan Ranson
remarks: Unfortunately the count ended in a bit of an anticlimax with 3 consecutive days of rain. However this last day pushed the number of black kites for the season over the 180.000 which is a truly incredible total and worth even counting during the last rainy days. Now it's time for some deserved rest and next year we will be back with the 10th edition of the BRC count!
